## [ENVIRONMENT RUNTIME & LANGUAGE]

Write all code strictly targeting the following language specification. Apply the correct module syntax, standard library APIs, and runtime-specific idioms throughout. Do not use syntax, features, or tools that do not belong to this target.

TypeScript (Node.js v22+ / ESM). The compiled output is a single ESM entry point executed directly by Node.js through the `bin` field of `package.json`.

<source_ref ids="S1,S2" />

### Approved Dependency Whitelist

You are strictly forbidden from installing or importing any package outside of this list:

Only use standard native Node.js APIs (`fs/promises`, `path`) and standard regex. Do not use external parsers or heavy dependencies.

- `@openhint/transpiler` — the sole runtime dependency; provides `parse`, `compile`, and the `is` error predicate.
- No additional runtime packages. Use only Node.js built-in modules for process I/O.

<source_ref ids="S1,S2" />

## [COMPILATION & TESTING PIPELINES]

The following commands validate this codebase. All generated code, configuration files, and project structure must remain compatible with these pipelines. Do not generate anything that breaks them.

- tsc for compilation
- makefile for better development and maintenance experience.

- `make build-js` to compile TypeScript to the release directory.
- `make test-js` to run the vitest suite.

<source_ref ids="S2,S3,S4,S5,S6,S7,S8,S9" />

## [CRITICAL SYSTEM MANDATES]

The following mandates are non-negotiable system-level constraints. Every function, data access pattern, and error path must satisfy all mandates listed here without exception:

- Write nothing to stdout except the final compiled prompt string.
- Write all diagnostic messages, usage text, and error details exclusively to stderr.
- Exit code 0 on success; exit code 1 on any failure.
- Never swallow an error silently — always emit the message before exiting.

- Do not write to stdout, stderr, or call `process.exit()`.
- Do not catch errors; let them propagate to the CLI entry point.
- Always pass `--print` so `claude` runs in non-interactive single-response mode; omitting it would open an interactive session the caller cannot control.
- Never pass the prompt as a command-line argument — always via stdin through `spawnAgent`.

- Do not write to stdout, stderr, or call `process.exit()`.
- Do not catch errors; let them propagate.
- Always pass the prompt via stdin — never as a command-line argument.

- Do not call `process.exit()`, write to stdout, or write to stderr — all I/O and lifecycle decisions belong to the CLI entry point.
- Do not catch errors thrown by the transpiler; let them propagate.
- In `spawnAgent`, never buffer the child process's stdout or stderr — always inherit so the agent's output streams to the terminal in real time.

- Use only `node:fs/promises` and `node:path` for all file system operations; do not shell out.
- The idempotency guard is the presence of the string `'## HINT'` anywhere in the file; do not re-append if the marker exists regardless of surrounding content.
- Do not write anything to stdout or stderr; all outcomes surface through returned values or thrown `AppError` values.
- Do not call `process.exit()`.

